[32m+[m[32m## Framework Choice: Why LangGraph[m
[32m+[m
[32m+[m[32mWe evaluated three options:[m
 [m
 | Framework | Pros | Cons | Verdict |[m
 |-----------|------|------|---------|[m
[31m-| **LangGraph** | Native state management, conditional edges, built-in retry limits | Heavy dependency, hides control flow, harder to debug | ❌ |[m
[31m-| **LlamaIndex** | Good for simple RAG, built-in retrievers | Less flexible for custom agentic loops | ❌ |[m
[31m-| **Custom Python** | Full control, explicit flow, easy to debug, zero lock-in | Must build state management manually | ✅ |[m
[32m+[m[32m| **LangGraph** | Native state management, conditional edges, built-in retry/recursion limits, typed state with reducers | Slightly more boilerplate than raw Python | ✅ **Chosen** |[m
[32m+[m[32m| **LlamaIndex** | Good for simple RAG, built-in retrievers | Less flexible for custom agentic loops, harder to add conditional branching | ❌ |[m
[32m+[m[32m| **Custom Python** | Full control, no dependencies | Must build state management, loop control, and graph execution from scratch | ❌ |[m
 [m
[31m- [m
[32m+[m[32m**Why LangGraph won:**[m
[32m+[m[32m1. The pipeline has 12 nodes with conditional branching — LangGraph's `StateGraph` + `add_conditional_edges` maps directly to this.[m
[32m+[m[32m2. The `Annotated` typed state with reducers (`replace_value`, `merge_list`) prevents state corruption when nodes return partial updates.[m
[32m+[m[32m3. Built-in `recursion_limit` provides a safety net against infinite loops without manual tracking.[m
[32m+[m[32m4. The graph compiles to a runnable that can be invoked with a single `graph.invoke()` call.[m
